# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alaska-statehood-act
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] The **1919 Motor Transport Corps convoy** was a long distance convoy (described as a Motor Truck Trip with a "Truck Train") carried out by the U.S.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Army Motor Transport Corps that drove over 3,000 mi (4,800 km) on the historic Lincoln Highway from Washington, D.C., to Oakland, California and then was ferried across the San Francisco Bay, ending their journey in San Francisco.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] McMahon were the respective expedition and train commanders and civilian Henry C.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Ostermann of the Lincoln Highway Association was the pilot (guide).
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Official observers included those from the Air Service, A.S.A.P., Coast and Field Artillery, Medical Corps, Ordnance, Signal Corps and Tank Corps including the then Brevet Lieutenant Colonel Dwight D.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] The Signal Corps filmed convoy events; and the civilians of the Goodyear band were transported from Chicago in one of the trucks.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] In addition to 230 road incidents (stops for adjustments, extrications, breakdowns, & accidents) resulting in 9 vehicles retiring, the convoy of "24 expeditionary officers, 15 War Department staff observation officers, and 258 enlisted men" had 21 injured en route who did not complete the trip.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Although some "were really competent drivers" by the end, the majority of soldiers were "raw recruits with little or no military training"; and except for the Motor Supply Company E commander (1st Lt Daniel H.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] In addition to engineer and quartermaster units; the convoy had 2 truck companies of the 433rd Motor Supply Train; a medical unit with surgeon, medical, and dental officers; and a Field Artillery Detachment which provided the Maxwell crawler tractor operated by a civilian.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] The 81 total vehicles and trailers included "34 heavy cargo trucks, 4 light delivery trucks", 2 mobile machine shops, 1 blacksmith shop, and 1 wrecking truck, actually a Militor "Artillery Wheeled Tractor" that once towed 9 trucks at once and was equipped with a power winch.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Additional vehicle manufacturers included Cadillac, Dodge, F.W.D., Garford, Harley-Davidson & Indian (motorcycles), Liberty (trucks & a 2-wheel kitchen cart), Mack, Packard, Riker, Standardized, Trailmobile (two 4-wheel kitchen trailers), and White.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] The heavy trucks included three examples of each of three wartime commercial models in the 3 to 5-1/2 ton range being considered for continued service (FWD, Mack and Riker) along with eleven 1-1/2 ton trucks from Garford, GMC, Packard and White.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] The four "light delivery trucks" were 3/4 ton Dodges and the remainder were 3 ton Class B Standardized Military "Liberty" trucks.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Dealers en route supplied gasoline and tires to the convoy and the Firestone Tire and Rubber Company provided 2 trucks (Packard & White, each 2-ton) fitted with "giant cord pneumatic" tires that carried spare standard tires.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] One Firestone truck detoured to Reno, Nevada, to have a new giant tire mounted.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Six vehicles were chosen to evaluate Dixon's Graphite Grease to see if it provided worthwhile benefits.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] In the course of its journey, the convoy broke and repaired dozens of wooden bridges (14 in Wyoming alone) and "practically" all roadways were unpaved from Illinois through Nevada.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] The convoy travelled up to 32 mph (51 km/h), and the schedule was for 18 mph (29 km/h) to average 15 mph (24 km/h).
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] The actual average for the 3,250 mi (5,230 km) covered in 573.5 hours was 5.65 mph (9.09 km/h) over the 56 travel days for an average of 10.24 hours per travel day.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Six rest days without convoy travel were at East Palestine, Ohio; Chicago Heights, Illinois; Denison, Iowa; North Platte, Nebraska; Laramie, Wyoming; and Carson City, Nevada.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Inexperience caused a great deal of unnecessary delays and breakdowns in the early going.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Both Lieutenant Jackson and Lieutenant Colonel Eisenhower described the Motor Transport Corps soldiers as raw and undisciplined though Jackson also reported that they were generally well behaved.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] The officers and men of the Engineer, Medical and Ordinance (maintenance) detachments were described as more experienced and better trained.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Both Eisenhower and Jackson reported that organization and discipline improved over the course of the expedition.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] After a few weeks on the road, the most skilled and responsible men were assigned as drivers or co-drivers of specific vehicles with full responsibility for their operations and maintenance.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] A preventive maintenance routine of evening servicing and morning inspections was instituted to reduce preventable breakdowns.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Eisenhower reported that the experience gained on the relatively good roads in the earlier, easier part of the trip proved invaluable in the heavier going further west.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Lieutenant Jackson reported that the assignment of a dedicated mess officer in Nebraska greatly improved the food for the second half of the journey.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] The convoy was preceded by a publicity officer travelling one day ahead by automobile to prepare for the arrival of the main body.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Two junior officers scouted ahead of the main body on motorcycles, signaling the route to the rest of the convoy using a simple but effective system of blue paper triangles tacked to trees and fences.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] The other motorcycles were used to carry messages up and down the length of the convoy.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] The Engineer detachment led the main body with the 5-1/2 ton Mack that carried the Artillery detachment's Maxwell crawler tractor.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] As the largest and most heavily laden vehicle, it was most likely to get stuck, and the crawler and the engineers would be readily at hand to extract it.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] The engineers were responsible for inspecting each bridge as the convoy came to it.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Weak bridges were reinforced or repaired, sometimes after a truck fell through them.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Bridges too small or weak for the Mack had to be bypassed.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] The Ordnance detachment brought up the rear, repairing or towing disabled vehicles as necessary.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] The trucks generally carried full capacity loads as one of the goals of the expedition was testing their performance.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] At many stops along the way, the convoy was escorted into town by local dignitaries and feted with church bells, parades, concerts, picnics, dances and banquets.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] For example, the log entry for 18 July reads (in part) "At 8:00 A.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] M. halted by request in Churubusco, Ind for 10 min., while refreshments were served by local Red Cross Canteen Service.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Met and escorted through South Bend by Major [sic] F.R.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Carson, Chief of Policy [sic] Peter Kline, Fire Chief I.A.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Sorbell, Secretary Chamber of Commerce Jos.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Kelley, Reception Comm. of prominent citizens, 3 Fire Companies and two bands, furnished by the Chamber of Commerce and the Goodrich Company." One pedestrian was struck, non-fatally, in Valparaiso, Indiana.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] In western Wyoming, Eisenhower and a companion convinced the convoy that an Indian attack was imminent.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Sentinels were posted that night, but when Ike and friend exchanged *warrior yelps* outside the perimeter, a young officer on guard discharged his weapon.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] They had to stop a telegram being sent to the War Office reporting an encounter with hostile Indians.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Convoy delays required extra encampments at Sewickley, Pennsylvania (11/12 July); Gothenburg, Nebraska (2/3 August); and Ogallala, Nebraska (5/6); which delayed arrival at Evanston, Wyoming, to 16 August instead of the scheduled 13 August.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] To the next control point, the convoy travelled 166 miles (267 km) instead of the planned 88 and used extra camps at Echo, Utah (17/18), and Ogden, Utah (18/19); arriving at Salt Lake City on the 19th (instead of the 14th).
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Despite travelling on 24 August rest day, the convoy fell behind an additional day using 4 travel days instead of the 2 scheduled travel days from Orr's Ranch, Utah, through the Great Salt Lake Desert to Ely, Nevada; where the convoy arrived on the 24th (v.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] An extra travel day on "mining roads" was used between Ely and Austin, Nevada; where the convoy arrived on the 27th (v.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] 20th), 348 mi (560 km) short of the scheduled point for the 27th (Sacramento).
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] The convoy remained 7 days behind schedule through Oakland, California, where it arrived 5 September at 4 pm (v. the 29th).
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Forgoing a rest day originally scheduled for the day after arriving in Oakland, the convoy instead ferried to San Francisco the next morning 6 days behind schedule and parked at the Presidio of San Francisco.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] In addition to transporting New York's Medal of Joan of Arc for San Francisco's Palace of Fine Arts, the convoy had four objectives; and Ordnance Department and Tank Corps observers completed their reports in October.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Study & observe "the terrain and standard army vehicles": .
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Lieutenant Colonel Eisenhower went on note that the variety of vehicles made it difficult to keep the convoy together and none of the vehicles had been properly tested or adjusted before starting out, which along with the raw nature of the troops caused a lot of unnecessary stops and breakdowns.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Lieutenant Jackson, the Ordnance Department Observer, submitted a detailed report on the performance of all of the convoy's vehicles.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] The Cadillac and Dodge passenger cars and light trucks were found to be generally satisfactory, though the hood latches on the Dodge proved insufficiently durable.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Of the transport trucks, the FWD proved the most satisfactory and the Garford the least, the former due to its mechanical reliability and all wheel drive and the latter due to a fragile cooling system, though the Standard B "Liberty" trucks were actually the most towed trucks in the convoy.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] The White, GMC, Riker, Packard and Mack trucks also proved satisfactory, though the latter's chain drive rendered them unsuitable for poor roads, and the larger motorcycles would have benefitted from more robust tires.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Most of the failures that were not caused by operator error (primarily poor lubrication and over-revving on downgrades) were due to the effects of the constant dust, vibration and pounding on the carburetors, ignition systems, bushings, fasteners and bearings.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] The various trailers were also evaluated (most received failing grades) and the graphite grease was determined to provide significant benefits.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1919-motor-transport-corps-convoy] Finally, the Maxwell and Militor tractors were praised for their overall reliability and mechanical superiority, as the trip could not have been completed without them.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Both the mushers and their dogs were portrayed as heroes in the newly popular medium of radio and received headline coverage in newspapers across the United States.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Balto, the lead sled dog on the final stretch into Nome, became the most famous canine celebrity of the era after Rin Tin Tin, and his statue is a popular tourist attraction in both New York City's Central Park and downtown Anchorage, Alaska.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Togo's team covered much of the most dangerous parts of the route and ran the farthest: Togo's team covered 261 miles (420 km) while Balto's team ran 55 miles (89 km).
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] From November to July, the port on the southern shore of the Seward Peninsula of the Bering Sea was icebound and inaccessible by steamship.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The only link to the rest of the world during the winter was the Iditarod Trail, which ran 938 miles (1,510 km) from the port of Seward in the south, across several mountain ranges and the vast Alaska Interior, to the town of Nome.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In Alaska and other subarctic regions, the primary source of mail and needed supplies in 1925 was the dog sled.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Within a decade, bush flying became the dominant method of transportation during the winter months.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In the winter of 1924–1925, Curtis Welch was the only doctor in Nome.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He and four nurses, working at the small Maynard Columbus Hospital, served the town and the surrounding area.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] After discovering the hospital's entire batch of diphtheria antitoxin had expired, Welch placed an order for more.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] However, the replacement shipment did not arrive before the port was closed by ice for the winter, and more could not be shipped in to Nome until spring.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In the next few weeks, after the number of cases grew and four children were dead—whom Welch had not been able to autopsy—he became increasingly concerned about diphtheria.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] By mid-January 1925, Welch officially diagnosed the first case of diphtheria in a three-year-old boy who died only two weeks after first becoming ill.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The following day, when a seven-year-old girl presented the same symptoms of diphtheria, Welch attempted to administer some of the expired antitoxin to see if it might still have any effect, but the girl died a few hours later.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Realizing that an epidemic was imminent, Welch called Nome's mayor, George Maynard, that same evening to arrange an emergency town council meeting.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The council immediately implemented a quarantine.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The following day, on January 22, 1925, Welch sent radio telegrams to all other major towns in Alaska alerting them of the public health risk.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He also requested assistance from the U.S.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Despite the quarantine, there were over 20 confirmed cases of diphtheria and at least 50 more at risk by the end of January.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Without antitoxin, it was expected that in the surrounding region's population of around 10,000 people, the mortality rate could be close to 100 percent.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] A previous influenza pandemic had hit the area in 1918, causing fatalities in about 50 percent of the native population of Nome and 8% of the native population of Alaska.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] More than 1,000 people died in northwest Alaska, and approximately 2,000 across the state.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The majority were Alaska Natives who did not have any resistance to either disease.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] At the January 24 meeting of the board of health, superintendent Mark Summers of the Hammon Consolidated Gold Fields proposed a dogsled relay using two fast teams.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] One would start at Nenana, Alaska, the closest railhead on the Alaska Railroad, and the other at Nome, and they would meet roughly halfway in the town of Nulato.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The trip from Nulato to Nome normally took 30 days.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Curtis Welch estimated that the serum would last only six days under the brutal conditions of the trail.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Summers's employee, the Norwegian sled dog trainer and musher Leonhard Seppala, was chosen for the 630-mile (1,014 km) round trip from Nome to Nulato and back.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He had previously made the run in a record-breaking four days, won the All-Alaska Sweepstakes three times, and had become famous for his athletic ability and rapport with his Siberian huskies.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] His lead dog, the 12-year-old Togo, was equally famous for his leadership, intelligence, and ability to sense danger.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Maynard proposed flying the antitoxin by plane.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In 1925, planes were a relatively new technology, and Alaska's harsh winter weather made them unreliable.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Several test flights had been conducted the previous year between Fairbanks and McGrath, Alaska, to determine how well a reliable aircraft could handle the winter conditions.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The longest test flight flew a distance of only 260 miles (420 km), a little under half the necessary distance between Nenana and Nome.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The only planes operating in Alaska in 1925 were three vintage biplanes, which had been dismantled for the winter.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Their open cockpits and water-cooled engines would make these planes unfit for the trip as well.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Although it was potentially quicker, the proposal to deliver the antitoxin by flight was rejected by the board of health.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Instead, they voted unanimously for the dogsled relay.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala was notified that evening and immediately began preparations for the trip.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Public Health Service had located 1.1 million units of serum in West Coast hospitals which could be shipped to Seattle, Washington, and then transported to Alaska.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The next ship north would not arrive in Seattle until January 31, and it would take another six to seven days to arrive in Seward.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] On January 26, 300,000 forgotten units of the antitoxin were located in a hospital in Anchorage.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The supply was wrapped in glass vials, then padded quilts, and finally a metallic cylinder weighing a little over 20 pounds (9 kg).
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] At Governor Scott Bone's order, it was immediately shipped to Nenana and arrived the next day.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] While not sufficient to defeat the epidemic, the 300,000 units could slow the spread of the disease until the larger shipment arrived.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The mail route from Nenana to Nome spanned 674 miles (1,085 km) in total.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] It crossed the barren Alaska Interior, following the Tanana River for 137 miles (220 km) to the village Tanana at the junction with the Yukon River, and then following the Yukon for 230 miles (370 km) to Kaltag.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The route then passed west 90 miles (140 km) over the Kaltag Portage to Unalakleet on the shore of Norton Sound.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The route then continued for 208 miles (335 km) northwest around the southern shore of the Seward Peninsula with no protection from gales and blizzards, including a 42-mile (68 km) stretch across the shifting ice of the Bering Sea.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Edward Wetzler, the US Postal Service inspector for Nenana, contacted Tom Parson, an agent of the Northern Commercial Company, contracted to deliver mail between Fairbanks and Unalakleet.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Telephones and telegraphs turned the drivers back to their assigned roadhouses.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The mail carriers held a revered position in the territory, and were the best dog mushers in Alaska.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The majority of relay drivers across the Interior were native Athabaskans, direct descendants of the original dog mushers.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The first musher in the relay was "Wild Bill" Shannon, who was handed the 20 pounds (9 kg) package at the train station in Nenana on January 27 at 9:00 pm AKST by night.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Despite a temperature of −50 °F (−46 °C), Shannon left immediately with his team of 9 inexperienced dogs, led by Blackie.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The temperature began to drop, and the team was forced onto the colder ice of the river because the trail had been destroyed by horses.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Despite jogging alongside the sled to keep warm, Shannon developed hypothermia.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He reached Minto at 3 am, with parts of his face black from frostbite.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] After warming the serum by the fire and resting for four hours, Shannon dropped three dogs and left with the remaining 8.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The three dogs died shortly after Shannon returned for them, and a fourth may have died as well.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Half-Athabaskan Edgar Kalland arrived in Minto the night before, and was sent back to Tolovana, traveling 70 mi (110 km) the day before the relay.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Shannon and his team arrived in bad condition at 11 am, and handed over the serum.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] After warming the serum in the roadhouse, Kalland headed into the forest.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The temperature had fallen to −56 °F (−49 °C), causing Kalland's hands to freeze to the sled's handlebar, requiring the owner of the Manley Hot Springs roadhouse to pour boiling water on the birch wood bar for thawing.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] No new cases of diphtheria were diagnosed on January 28, but two new cases were diagnosed on January 29.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The quarantine had been obeyed, but lack of diagnostic tools and the contagiousness of the strain rendered it ineffective.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] More units of serum were discovered around Juneau the same day.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] While no count exists, the estimate based on weight is roughly 125,000 units, enough to treat 4 to 6 patients.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The crisis had become headline news in newspapers, including in San Francisco, Cleveland, Washington D.C., and New York, and spread to the radio sets which were just becoming common.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The storm system from Alaska hit the contiguous United States, bringing record lows to New York, and freezing the Hudson River.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Maynard and Alaskan House Delegate Daniel Sutherland renewed their campaign for flying the remaining serum by plane.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Different proposals included flying a large aircraft 2,000 miles (3,200 km) from Seattle to Nome, carrying a plane to the edge of the pack ice via Navy ship and launching it, and the original plan of flying the serum from Fairbanks.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Despite receiving headline coverage across the country and support from Arctic explorer Roald Amundsen, the plans were rejected by experienced pilots, the Navy, and Governor Bone.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] As publisher and editor of the *Fairbanks Daily News-Miner* newspaper, William Fentress Thompson harshly criticized government officials for inaction and funded a private fleet of planes.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In response, Governor Bone decided to speed up the relay, authorizing additional drivers for Seppala's leg of the relay, so they could travel without rest.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala was still scheduled to cover the most dangerous leg, the shortcut across Norton Sound, but the telephone and telegraph systems bypassed the small villages he was passing through, and there was no way to tell him to wait at Shaktoolik.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The plan relied on the driver from the north catching Seppala on the trail.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Summers arranged for drivers along the last leg, including Seppala's colleague Gunnar Kaasen.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] From Manley Hot Springs, the serum passed through largely Athabascan hands before George Nollner delivered it to Charlie Evans at Bishop Mountain on January 30 at 3 am.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The temperature had warmed slightly, but at −62 °F (−52 °C), was dropping again.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Evans relied on his lead dogs when he passed through ice fog where the Koyukuk River, flowing into the Yukon, had broken through and surged over the ice, but forgot to protect the groins of his two short-haired mixed breed lead dogs with rabbit skins.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Both dogs collapsed with frostbite, with Evans having to take their place himself pulling the sled.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He arrived at 10 am; both dogs were dead.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Tommy Patsy departed within half an hour.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The transport of the serum then parted ways with the Yukon River as the river turned south and the trail crossed the Kaltag Portage west to the coast.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Gonangnan saw the signs of a storm brewing, and decided not to take the shortcut across the dangerous ice of the Sound.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala was not there, but Henry Ivanoff was waiting just in case.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] On January 30, the number of cases in Nome had reached 27 and the antitoxin was depleted.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] According to a reporter living in Nome, "All hope is in the dogs and their heroic drivers ...
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Nome appears to be a deserted city." With the report of Gonangnan's progress on January 31, Welch believed the serum would arrive there in February.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Leonhard Seppala and his dog sled team, with his lead dog Togo, travelled 91 miles (146 km) from Nome from January 27 to January 31 into the oncoming storm.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] They took the shortcut across the Norton Sound, and headed toward Shaktoolik.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The temperature in Nome was a relatively warm −20 °F (−29 °C), but in Shaktoolik, the temperature was estimated at −30 °F (−34 °C), and the gale force winds causing a wind chill of −85 °F (−65 °C).
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Henry Ivanoff's team ran into a reindeer and got tangled up just outside Shaktoolik.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala still believed he had more than 100 mi (160 km) to the original relay point in Nulato to go and had raced to get off the Norton Sound before the storm hit.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He was passing the team when Ivanoff shouted, "The serum!
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala turned around with the serum but it was dark by the time he got to Ungalik.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] But with the news of the worsening epidemic Ivanoff had shared, he decided not to stop and once again set out to brave the storm across the 20 miles (32 km) of exposed open ice of the Norton Sound.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The temperature was estimated at −30 °F (−34 °C), but the wind chill with the gale force winds was −85 °F (−65 °C).
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Togo led the team in a straight line through the dark, and they arrived at the roadhouse in Isaac's Point on the other side at 8 pm.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In one day, they had travelled 84 mi (135 km), averaging 8 mph (13 km/h).
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The team rested, and departed at 2 am into the full power of the storm.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] During the night, the temperature dropped to −40 °F (−40 °C), and the wind increased to storm force (at least 65 mph [105 km/h]).
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] While they slept, it had blown out to sea all the ice Seppala had just crossed.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] There was still some ice close to shore for the next part of their journey along the coast, but it was rough and starting to break up too.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] They stuck close to shore, and Togo picked his way carefully until they were back on solid ground.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Next they had to cross Little McKinley Mountain (1,200 feet [370 m]), another of the toughest parts of the trail because of the many up-and-down ridges.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The total elevation climbed in that section of over 8 miles (13 km) is 5,000 feet (1,500 m).
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] After descending to the next roadhouse in Golovin, Seppala passed the serum to Charlie Olsen on February 1 at 3 pm.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] On February 1, the number of cases in Nome rose to 28.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The serum en route was sufficient to treat 30 people.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] With the powerful blizzard raging and winds of 80 mph (130 km/h), Welch ordered a stop to the relay until the storm passed, reasoning that a delay was better than the risk of losing all the serum.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Messages were left at Solomon and Point Safety before the lines went dead.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Olsen was blown off the trail, and suffered severe frostbite in his hands while putting blankets on his dogs.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He arrived at Bluff on February 1 at 7 pm in poor condition.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Gunnar Kaasen waited until 10 pm for the storm to break, but it only got worse and the drifts would soon block the trail, so he departed into a headwind.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Kaasen traveled through the night, through drifts, and river overflow over the 600-foot (183 m) Topkok Mountain.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Balto led the team through visibility so poor that Kaasen could not always see the dogs harnessed closest to the sled.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He was two miles (3 km) past Solomon before he realized it, and kept going.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The winds after Solomon were so severe that his sled flipped over and he almost lost the cylinder containing the serum when it fell off and became buried in the snow.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He also suffered frostbite when he had to use his bare hands to feel for the cylinder.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Kaasen reached Point Safety ahead of schedule on February 2, at 3 am.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Ed Rohn believed that Kaasen and the relay had halted at Solomon, so he was sleeping.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Since the weather was improving, it would take time to prepare Rohn's team, and Balto and the other dogs were moving well, Kaasen pressed on with the remaining 25 miles (40 km) to Nome, reaching Front Street at 5:30 am.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Not a single ampule was broken, and the antitoxin was thawed and ready by noon.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Together, the teams covered the 674 miles (1,085 km) in 1271⁄2 hours, which was considered a world record, done in extreme subzero temperatures in near-blizzard conditions and hurricane-force winds.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Margaret Curran from the Solomon Roadhouse was infected, which raised fears that the disease might spread from patrons of the roadhouse to other communities.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The 1.1 million units had left Seattle on January 31, and were not due by dog sled until February 8.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Welch asked for half the serum to be delivered by aircraft from Fairbanks.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He contacted Thompson and Sutherland, and Darling made a test flight the next morning.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] With his health advisor, Governor Bone concluded the cases in Nome were actually going down, and withheld permission, but preparations went ahead.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Navy moved a minesweeper north from Seattle, and the Signal Corps were ordered to light fires to guide the planes.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] By February 3, the original 300,000 units had proved to be still effective, and the epidemic was under control.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] A sixth death, probably unrelated to diphtheria, was widely reported as a new outbreak of the disease.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The batch from Seattle arrived on board the *Admiral Watson* on February 7.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Acceding to pressure, Governor Bone authorized half to be delivered by plane.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] On February 8, the first half of the second shipment began its trip by dog sled, while the plane failed to start when a broken radiator shutter caused the engine to overheat.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The plane failed the next day as well, and the mission was scrapped.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Thompson was gracious in his editorials.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The second relay included many of the same drivers, and also faced harsh conditions.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Ed Rohn delivered the serum to Nome during another blizzard after a 90 miles (140 km) run on February 15.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The death toll from diphtheria in Nome is officially listed as either 5, 6, or 7, but Welch later estimated there were probably at least 100 additional cases among "the Eskimo camps outside the city.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The Natives have a habit of burying their children without reporting the death." Forty-three new cases were diagnosed in 1926, but they were easily managed with the fresh supply of serum.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] All participants in the dogsleds received letters of commendation from President Calvin Coolidge, and the Senate stopped work to recognize the event.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Each musher during the first relay received a gold medal from the H.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The mayor of Los Angeles presented a bone-shaped key to the city to Balto in front of City Hall and silent-film actress Mary Pickford put a wreath around the canine's neck.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Poems and letters from children poured in, and spontaneous fundraising campaigns sprang up around the country.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Gunnar Kaasen and his team became celebrities and toured the West Coast from February 1925 to February 1926, and also starred in a 30-minute film entitled *Balto's Race to Nome*.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] A statue of Balto by sculptor Frederick Roth was unveiled in New York City's Central Park during a visit on December 15, 1925.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Balto and the other dogs later became part of a sideshow and lived in horrible conditions until they were rescued by George Kimble, who organized a fundraising campaign by the children of Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] On March 19, 1927, the dogs received a hero's welcome as they arrived at their permanent home at the Cleveland Zoo.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Because of his age, Balto was euthanized on March 14, 1933, at the age of 14.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He was mounted and placed on display in the Cleveland Museum of Natural History.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In October 1926, Seppala took Togo and his team on a tour from Seattle to California, and then across the Midwest to New England, and consistently drew huge crowds.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] They were featured at Madison Square Garden in New York City for 10 days, and Togo received a gold medal from Roald Amundsen.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In New England, Seppala's team of Siberians ran in many races, easily defeating the local Chinooks of Arthur Walden.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala entered into a partnership with Elizabeth M.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Ricker in Poland Spring, Maine, where many of his dogs went to live in retirement and contribute to their breeding program of Siberian sled dogs, including Togo, who sired many litters.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala visited Togo, and was by his side when he was euthanized on December 5, 1929, at the age of 16.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] After his death, Seppala had Togo preserved and mounted, and today the dog is on display in a glass case at the Iditarod museum in Wasilla, Alaska.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Togo's prowess as a sled dog also led to his strengths being preserved through breeding, with his descendants contributing to the "Seppala Siberian Sleddog", a sought after working sled dog line, as well as the mainstream show-stock Siberian Husky gene pool.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] None of the other mushers received the same degree of attention, though Wild Bill Shannon briefly toured with Blackie.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The media largely ignored the Alaska Native mushers, who covered two-thirds of the distance to Nome.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The serum race helped spur the Air Mail Act of 1925, which was signed into law on February 2.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The bill allowed private aviation companies to bid on mail delivery contracts.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Technology improved and, within a decade, air mail routes were established in Alaska.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The last mail delivery by private dog sled under contract took place in 1938, and the last U.S.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Post Office dog sled route closed in 1963.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Dog sledding remained popular in the rural interior but became nearly extinct when snowmobiles spread in the 1960s.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Mushing was revitalized as a recreational sport in the 1970s with the immense popularity of the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] While the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race, which runs more than 1,000 miles (1,600 km) from Anchorage to Nome, is based on the All-Alaska Sweepstakes, it has many traditions that commemorate the race to deliver the serum to Nome, especially Seppala and Togo.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The honorary musher for the first seven races was Leonhard Seppala.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Other serum run participants, including "Wild Bill" Shannon, Edgar Kalland, Bill McCarty, Charlie Evans, Edgar Nollner, Harry Pitka, and Henry Ivanoff have also been honored.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The 2005 Iditarod honored Jirdes Winther Baxter, the last known survivor of the epidemic.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The position is now known as Leonhard Seppala's Honorary Musher, the Leonhard Seppala Humanitarian Award is given to the musher who provides the best dog care while remaining competitive, and the Leonhard Seppala Heritage Grant is an Iditarod scholarship.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The two races follow the same route from Ruby to Nome.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] A reenactment of the serum run was held in 1975, which took six days longer than the 1925 serum run, or more than twice the total time.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Many of the participants were descendants of the original 20.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In 1985, President Ronald Reagan sent a letter of recognition to Charlie Evans, Edgar Nollner, and Bill McCarty, the only remaining survivors.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Nollner was the last to die, on January 18, 1999, of a heart attack.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The relay has been depicted in various media.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Shortly before World War II, Czech teacher and writer František Omelka was fascinated by the story, writing the novella *Štafeta* ("Relay") published in Czech in 1946.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] As an avid Esperantist, Omelka himself translated it into Esperanto, with subsequent translations into German, Dutch, Frisian, Icelandic, Chinese, Japanese, and English.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The serum run was featured in the 1949 animated short "Daffy Duck Hunt", where Daffy Duck describes his time in a freezer as though he were delivering serum on a dog sled.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In 1976, the story was retold in *Race Against Death: A True Story of the Far North,* by children's author Seymour Reit.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Reit's book was featured in a 1978 episode of *The Book Bird*, a PBS program where host John Robbins illustrated key scenes from the book being discussed.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The 1995 2D hand-drawn animated film *Balto* with music composed by James Roy Horner was loosely based on the events of the final leg of the serum run, although all of the characters besides Balto are fictional for family and children entertainments.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In 2013, a documentary titled *Icebound – The Greatest Dog Story Ever Told*, focused on the aftermath of the events.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] *The Great Alaskan Race*, a 2019 film, produced by Rebel Road Entertainment, is based on the serum run.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] *Togo*, produced by Walt Disney Pictures, debuted on December 20, 2019, on Disney+.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] There is much controversy surrounding Balto's role in the serum run and the statue in Central Park.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He then handed the serum off to Charlie Olson.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Olson carried it 25 miles (40 km) to Bluff where he turned it over to Gunnar Kaasen.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Kaasen was supposed to hand off the serum to Rohn at Port Safety, but Rohn had gone to sleep and Kaasen decided to keep going to Nome.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In all, Kaasen and Balto ran a total of 53 miles (85 km).
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] According to Togo's musher, Leonhard Seppala, who was also Balto's owner, Balto was a scrub freight dog that he left behind when he set out on the trip.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He also asserted that Kaasen's lead dog was actually a dog named Fox, but that news agents of the time thought that Balto was a more newsworthy name.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] No record exists of Seppala ever having used Balto as a leader in runs or races prior to 1925, and Seppala himself stated Balto "was never in a winning team".
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Because the pictures and video of Kaasen and Balto taken in Nome were recreated hours after their arrival once the sun had risen, speculation still exists as to whether Balto's position as lead dog was genuine, or was staged or exaggerated for media purposes.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The Central Park statue of Balto was modeled after Balto, but shows him wearing Togo's colors (awards).
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Katy Steinmetz, writing in *Time* magazine, also thought that Togo was the greatest sled dog of all time.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Mushers (in order) and the distances they covered.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Most legs were planned to be about 25 miles (40 km) long, generally accepted as an "extreme day's mush".
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] From March 9 to June 1, 1948, voters of the Republican Party elected delegates to the 1948 Republican National Convention, in part to choose the party nominee for president in the 1948 United States presidential election.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The 1948 Republican National Convention was held from June 21 to June 25, 1948, in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Dewey was nominated for president and California Governor Earl Warren was nominated for vice president.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Dewey and Warren went on to lose the general election to the Democratic Party's ticket of incumbent President Harry S.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Both the Republican Party and the Democratic Party courted Dwight D.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Eisenhower, the most popular United States general of World War II.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Eisenhower's political views were unknown in 1948.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] He was, later events would prove, a moderate Republican, but in 1948 he flatly refused the nomination of any political party.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] With Eisenhower refusing to run, the contest for the Republican nomination was between New York Governor Thomas E.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Dewey, former Minnesota Governor Harold Stassen, General Douglas MacArthur, Ohio Senator Robert A.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Taft and California Governor Earl Warren.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Governor Dewey, who had been the Republican nominee in 1944, was regarded as the frontrunner when the primaries began.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Dewey was the acknowledged leader of the GOP's powerful eastern establishment; in 1946 he had been re-elected Governor of New York by the largest margin in state history.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Dewey's handicap was that many Republicans disliked him; he often struck observers as cold, stiff and condescending.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Senator Taft was the leader of the GOP's conservative wing.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] He opened his campaign in 1947 by attacking the Democratic Party's domestic policy and foreign policy.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] In foreign policy, Taft was a non-interventionist who opposed many of the alliances the U.S. government had made with other nations to fight the Cold War with the Soviet Union; he believed that the nation should concentrate on its own problems and avoid "imperial entanglements".
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] On domestic issues, Taft and his fellow conservatives wanted to abolish many of the New Deal social welfare programs that had been created in the 1930s; they regarded these programs as too expensive and harmful to business interests.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Taft had two major weaknesses: he was seen as a plodding, dull campaigner, and he was viewed by most party leaders as being too conservative and controversial to win a presidential election.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Taft's support was limited to his native Midwestern United States and parts of the Southern United States.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The "surprise" candidate of 1948 was Stassen, the former "boy wonder" of Minnesota politics.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Stassen had been elected governor of Minnesota at the age of 31; he resigned as governor in 1943 and served in the United States Navy in World War II.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] In 1945 he had served on the committee which created the United Nations.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Stassen was widely regarded as the most "liberal" of the Republican candidates, yet as the primaries continued he was criticized for being vague on many issues.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] These candidates participated in multiple state primaries or were included in multiple major national polls.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The following candidates did not actively campaign for any state's presidential primary, but may have had their name placed on the ballot by supporters or may have sought to influence to selection of un-elected delegates or sought the support of uncommitted delegates.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The following candidates ran only in their home state's primary or caucus for the purpose of controlling its delegate slate at the convention and did not appear to be considered national candidates by the media.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Dewey declined to enter the campaign actively while the New York legislature remained in session.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] In New Hampshire, that meant Dewey relied on the state's Governor, Charles M.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Dale, and other supporters to deliver the eight-person delegation to his column.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Dewey took six of the state's eight delegates, and the most popular Dewey delegate outpolled the most popular Stassen delegate by 28,000 votes to 21,000.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Wisconsin had proven decisive in 1944 by eliminating Wendell Willkie from the campaign after a poor showing; in 1948, it evolved into a contest between native son Douglas MacArthur and neighbor Harold Stassen of Minnesota.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Dewey, maintaining his front-runner approach, remained in Albany and nearly declined to enter the primary, submitting his name only halfheartedly at the last minute.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The Stassen campaign benefited from the large Scandinavian population and the support of Senator Joseph McCarthy, while MacArthur, still in Tokyo, was supported by the La Follette family, the Milwaukee Sentinel, and many of Dewey's 1944 campaigners.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] McCarthy, a Catholic, criticized MacArthur for his remarriage and divorce; the attack was aimed at the state's large Catholic population.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Stassen also succeeded by appealing to both young and liberal voters (through internationalist foreign policy) and conservative and ethnic voters (by calling for a national ban on the Communist Party).
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] In an indirect attack on Dewey, he noted that forty percent of the nation's communists resided in New York.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Though he did not initially campaign in the state, Dewey was weakened by Wisconsin; the leading candidates and other enemies, like former Congressman Hamilton Fish III, had the opportunity to attack him while he remained in New York.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Stassen won a triumph over MacArthur, taking nineteen delegates to the General's eight.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Dewey was shut out, though he captured ten delegates in Oklahoma.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] One week after Wisconsin, Stassen again bested Dewey in Nebraska.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Dewey had made a much stronger effort there, having left Wisconsin early to deliver a foreign policy speech in Lincoln.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The two were joined on the campaign trail in Nebraska by Senator Robert A.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Given a break in the Senate schedule for Lincoln's birthday, Taft campaigned in Nebraska, as well as Indiana, Illinois, Minnesota, and Colorado in the span of one week.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Taft was unpopular in the state over his opposition to farm subsidies and unable to campaign until Senate business concluded; he likely preferred to bypass the state altogether.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] His hand was forced, however, by an independent committee which placed the names of all candidates on the ballot and Senator Hugh A.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Butler, who offered Taft the support of his political organization and personally planned a three-day campaign trip for him; he reluctantly agreed.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The result was disaster for Taft, who finished a distant third (with only twice the vote of the non-candidate Vandenberg) and a boost for Stassen, who won a clean victory over Dewey.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Now with clear momentum, Stassen appeared to be the favorite for the nomination; he led in the Gallup poll for the first time and was the betting favorite to win the crucial Oregon primary, his next showdown with Dewey.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Faced with the definite prospect of a third failed presidential campaign, the press began to write Dewey off.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Dewey thus decided to stake his political career on Oregon and left for the state on April 20, to establish a campaign and barnstorm for votes.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] In January, Stassen made a serious violation of political etiquette by challenging a candidate in his home state.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Though Taft personally appealed to Stassen to desist for both candidacies' sakes, the Minnesotan pressed forward with a January 25 announcement that he would controversially file in Ohio, angering Taft and his conservative supporters.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Stassen reasoned that he must campaign in the state, since he relied entirely on popular support without establishment backing.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] After losing Nebraska, Taft hurried home, where he would campaign from April 17 until primary day, speaking eight to ten times per day.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Stassen focused his strength by running a slate of only twenty-three delegates out of a possible fifty-three.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Only one, a respected former Ohio Supreme Court justice, ran at-large; the other twenty-two ran in carefully selected districts in the urban centers of Akron, Cleveland, Dayton, and Youngstown.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Stassen presumed that voters in these districts would oppose Taft for his sponsorship of the anti-union Taft-Hartley Act.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Taft ridiculed Stassen for vagueness on the issues and took a firm stance in response against universal military training.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] He proudly spoke in favor of Taft-Hartley and also noted his public housing and education aid bills.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Richard Guylay utilized a radio campaign based on the principles of Gustave Le Bon, targeting veterans, young voters, and even union members with a direct appeal to emotion.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The primary was a resounding victory for Taft.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Out of the twenty-two district races, Stassen won only nine.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] His sole delegate at-large finished last.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Taft was particularly gratified by the support in industrial regions and told *Newsweek* that he had received a "new lease on life." Stassen had been dealt his first major blow and permanently alienated the conservative wing of the party in the process.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Privately, however, Taft acknowledged Ohio as a Pyrrhic victory; the effort strained his health and budget and gave Dewey a major leg up on both exhausted candidates,.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Beginning after his loss in Nebraska, Dewey prepared for a final stand in Oregon; he proclaimed to advisors that his political career was at stake.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Oregon was the only remaining state in which he would compete directly with Stassen for delegates elected by the voters.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] He had established a campaign strategy in the crucial state in July 1947 with Herbert Brownell and local campaign veteran Ralph Moores, but by March, Moores warned Dewey that the campaign was adrift, and that it would be "desperately hard" to regain the advantage over Stassen.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The campaign established several interest group-specific campaigns, including those for sportsmen, teachers, dentists, lawyers, osteopaths, and farmers.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Among those constituencies targeted were the state's 12,000 black voters, who received mailings paying tribute to Dewey's efforts for a landmark anti-discrimination law and practice of race-blind hiring in state employment.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Dewey arrived in the state personally on May 1, campaigning throughout the state; within the first week, he met 35,000 voters.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] By May 12, Dewey forces had spent $71,000 in the state, most raised by Harold Talbott of the Chrysler Corporation.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The campaign would ultimately spend around $150,000, triple the state record, on billboards, radio spots, newspaper advertisements, and half-hour broadcasts.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The day before the primary, the Dewey campaign ran a telegram to every physician in the state, written by a former Stassen supporter who had soured on the candidate over socialized medicine.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Stassen, exhausted from his campaign in Ohio, found himself on the defensive for the first time and returned to Oregon earlier than he had planned.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] His opponents now criticized him for being vague on the issues, including Taft-Hartley, universal military training, and reciprocal tariffs.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] In the final week of the campaign, Stassen returned to anti-communism, the issue which had boosted his campaign to the forefront.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Stassen attacked Dewey for a "soft, coddling policy" on communism in the United States and challenged him to a direct debate on the issue—the first ever head-to-head radio debate between two presidential candidates.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Dewey accepted, and as the challenged party, chose the format, topic, and rules; the debate would be broadcast nationally on 900 stations from a quiet studio at KEX Portland.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The single topic: "Shall the Communist Party be outlawed in the United States?" The debate was heard by an estimated 40–80 million listeners throughout the country, one of the largest audiences in history.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] During the debate, Stassen read credited his wartime service and world travels for his belief than an international Communist network demanded immediate, punitive response.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Dewey responded with an extemporaneous criticism of the Mundt-Nixon Bill as a "grievous error," and pointed to the fact that Canada had banned communism but still hosted an international espionage ring in the Soviet embassy.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Dewey won the primary by just under 10,000 votes; Stassen no longer had a direct path to the nomination and had failed at establishing himself as the clear popular favorite.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Though Stassen had entered the primaries as the presumable heir to Wendell Willkie as the leader of liberal Republicans, the debate over communism had flipped his and Dewey's positions.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] He now entered negotiations with Taft to block Dewey's nomination at the convention.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The 1948 Republican National Convention was held in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] It was the first presidential convention to be shown on television.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] As the convention opened, Dewey was seen as having a large lead in the delegate count.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] His major opponents – Taft, Stassen, and Senator Arthur H.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Vandenberg of Michigan – met in Taft's hotel suite to plan a "stop-Dewey" movement.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] However, a key obstacle soon developed when the three men refused to unite behind a single candidate to oppose Dewey.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Instead, all three men simply agreed to try to hold their own delegates in the hopes of preventing Dewey from obtaining a majority.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] This proved to be futile, as Dewey's efficient campaign team gathered up the delegates they needed to win the nomination.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] After the second round of balloting, Dewey was only 33 votes short of victory.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Taft then called Stassen and urged him to withdraw from the race and endorse him as Dewey's main opponent.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] When Stassen refused, Taft wrote a concession speech and had it read at the start of the third ballot; Dewey was then nominated by acclamation.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Dewey then chose popular Governor Earl Warren of California as his running mate.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1948-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Following the convention, most political experts in the news media rated the GOP ticket as an almost-certain winner over the Democrats.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] The **1952 Republican National Convention** was held at the International Amphitheatre in Chicago, Illinois from July 7 to 11, 1952, and nominated Dwight D.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Eisenhower of New York, nicknamed "Ike", for president and then Richard M.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] The 1952 Republican convention was the first political convention to be televised live, coast-to-coast.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Experiments in regionally broadcasting conventions took place during the Republican and Democratic conventions in 1948; however, 1952 was the first year in which networks carried nationwide coverage of political conventions.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Fixed cameras were placed at the back and the sides of the International Amphitheatre for the press to use collectively.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] None of these offered a straight shot of the podium on stage, so many networks supplemented their coverage with shots from their own portable cameras.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] The keynote speech was delivered by MacArthur, who had become a hero to Republicans after President Truman relieved him of command in 1951 because of their disagreement about how to prosecute the Korean War, and had hopes of obtaining the presidential nomination.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] In his address, MacArthur condemned the Truman administration for America's perceived loss of status on the international stage, including criticism of the Yalta Conference and the administration's handling of the war in Korea.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] MacArthur also criticized Truman on the domestic front, blaming his administration for wages that failed to keep pace with post-World War II inflation.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] The speech was not well received, and did nothing to aid MacArthur's presidential campaign.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] He curtailed his post-convention speeches and remained out of the public eye until after the election.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] The contest for the presidential nomination was expected to be a battle between the party's moderate-to-liberal and conservative wings.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Moderate and liberal Republicans (the "Eastern Establishment"), led by New York Governor Thomas E.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Dewey, the party's unsuccessful presidential nominee in 1944 and 1948, were largely supporters of Eisenhower or Warren.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] The conservative wing was led by Robert A.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Taft, who had unsuccessfully tried for the presidential nomination in 1940 and 1948.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] The Taft-dominated Republican National Committee supported Taft in the dispute.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] When delegate committees met to consider the issue before the convention convened, they sustained Eisenhower's position.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Stripped of 42 delegates from the disputed states, Taft's backers realized their chances of beating Eisenhower were slim.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] In his remarks during the delegate fight, Taft supporter Everett Dirksen harshly criticized Dewey and the moderate-to-liberal wing of the party, which had dominated it since 1940.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] McKeldin's nomination was seconded by Kansas Governor Edward F.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Arn, Oregon Republican Party Chairman Robert B.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Alberta Green, a delegate from West Plains, Missouri, and Hobson R.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Reynolds, an African American funeral director, state legislator from Philadelphia, and Director of the Civil Liberties Department of the Improved Benevolent and Protective Order of Elks of the World.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] After the nominations were completed, including speeches on behalf of Earl Warren, Harold Stassen, and Douglas MacArthur, the delegates proceeded to vote.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] After the first ballot, Eisenhower had 595 votes, nine short of the 604 required for the nomination, while Taft was a strong second with 500: Warren had 81, Stassen 20, and MacArthur 10.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Warren's backers refused to change their votes to Eisenhower because they still hoped for a deadlock that might enable Warren to obtain the nomination as a compromise choice.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Stassen had not received 10% of the vote, which freed his home state of Minnesota's delegates from their pledge to support him: all but one of the Stassen delegates, led by Warren E.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Burger, then changed their votes to Eisenhower, giving him 614 votes and securing him the presidential nomination.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] After the revised totals were announced, Taft and Warren supporters moved to unanimously nominate Eisenhower, which the delegates did.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] As soon as Eisenhower was nominated, he visited Taft personally to request his endorsement and obtain a promise that Taft would support the Republican ticket.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Taft immediately agreed, and loyally backed Eisenhower during the general election campaign.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] The nomination of Eisenhower in a single round of balloting marked the fifteenth time Republicans had selected their nominee on the first ballot.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] In the twenty-five national conventions the party had held since 1856, the party had averaged four ballots to select its presidential nominees.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Nixon's speech at a state Republican Party fundraiser in New York City on May 8, 1952, impressed Governor Thomas E.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Dewey, who was an Eisenhower supporter and had formed a pro-Eisenhower delegation from New York to attend the national convention.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] In a private meeting after the speech, Dewey suggested to Nixon that he would make a suitable vice presidential candidate on the ticket with Eisenhower.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Nixon attended the convention as a delegate pledged to Earl Warren and represented California on the convention's platform committee.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] In pre-convention remarks to reporters, Nixon touted Warren as the most prominent dark horse and suggested that if Warren was not the presidential nominee, Nixon's Senate colleague William Knowland would be a good choice for vice president.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] As the convention proceedings continued, Warren became concerned that Nixon was working for Eisenhower while ostensibly pledged to Warren.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Davis of the Hoover Institution at Stanford University, who had been a vice president at Columbia University while Eisenhower was the school's president, to tell Eisenhower that Warren resented such actions and wanted them to stop.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Eisenhower informed Davis that he did not oppose Warren, because if Taft and Eisenhower deadlocked, then Warren would be his first choice for the nomination.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] In the same conversation, Eisenhower indicated that if he won the nomination, Nixon would be his first choice for the vice presidency, because Eisenhower believed the party needed to promote leaders who were aggressive, capable, and young.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Eisenhower later developed a list of seven potential candidates, with Nixon's name at the top.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] After Eisenhower was nominated, his key supporters met to discuss vice presidential possibilities.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Eisenhower informed the group's chairman, Herbert Brownell Jr. that he did not wish to appear to dictate to the convention by formally sponsoring a single candidate, so the group reviewed several, including Taft, Everett Dirksen, and Alfred E.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Driscoll, all of whom they quickly rejected.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Dewey then raised Nixon's name; the group quickly concurred.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Brownell checked with Eisenhower, who indicated his approval.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Brownell then called Nixon to inform him that he was Eisenhower's choice.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Nixon accepted, then departed for Eisenhower's hotel room to discuss the details of the campaign and Eisenhower's plans for his vice president if the ticket was successful in the general election.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] A group of women delegates (led by former congresswoman Clare Boothe Luce) had hopes of putting forward a female vice presidential candidate.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] This group sought to nominate Senator Margaret Chase Smith of Maine, but Smith requested that her name not be used.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Noting that Eisenhower's supporters had coalesced around Nixon, Luce withdrew her nomination of Smith.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] The delegates soon assembled to formalize the selection.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Nixon asked Knowland to nominate him, and Knowland agreed.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Bricker declined Nixon's request to second the nomination, Driscoll agreed to do so.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-national-convention] There were no other candidates, and Nixon was nominated by acclamation.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] From March 11 to June 3, 1952, delegates were elected to the 1952 Republican National Convention.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The fight for the 1952 Republican nomination was largely between popular General Dwight D.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Dewey as the candidate of the party's liberal eastern establishment) and Senator Robert A.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Taft of Ohio, the longtime leader of the conservative wing.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Foreign policy during the Cold War was a major point of contention, with Eisenhower taking an interventionist stance and Taft favoring greater caution and avoidance of foreign alliances.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Eisenhower tended to accept many of the social welfare aspects of the New Deal, to which Taft was adamantly opposed.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Two other major candidates for the nomination, though never reaching the point of seriously challenging Eisenhower or Taft, were Governor of California and Dewey's 1948 running mate Earl Warren, and former Governor of Minnesota Harold Stassen, who had contended for the nomination in 1948 as well.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Taft, who was 62 when the campaign began and running his third presidential campaign, freely admitted that this would be his last chance to win the nomination.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Taft's weakness, which he was never able to overcome, was the fear of many party bosses that he was too conservative and controversial to win a presidential election.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The episode was reminiscent of the 1912 Republican National Convention forty years prior, in which Taft's father won the nomination over Theodore Roosevelt by similar means.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] In the general election on November 4, Eisenhower and his running mate, Senator Richard Nixon of California, defeated the Democratic party's ticket of Governor Adlai Stevenson II of Illinois, and Senator John Sparkman of Alabama.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Entering the 1952 election campaign, no Republican had been elected president since Herbert Hoover in 1928.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Republicans had only won a single national election during the period, in the 1946 elections to the 80th United States Congress.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Following their victory in 1946, Republicans were hopeful to win back the White House in 1948.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] With the progressive and Southern wings of the Democratic Party bolting from the presidential ticket and popular Governor of New York Thomas E.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Dewey leading their ticket for the second consecutive campaign, most expected a Republican victory but were surprised by the re-election of President Harry S.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Truman in one of the biggest upsets in the history of presidential elections.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Having lost the presidency three times, Dewey declined to make a fourth run.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Instead, the leading candidates were Dewey's main rivals for the 1948 nomination, Senator Robert A.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Taft of Ohio and former Governor Harold Stassen of Minnesota; and his 1948 running mate, Governor of California Earl Warren.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] During the 1948 campaign, James Roosevelt and Americans for Democratic Action attempted to draft popular World War II general Dwight D.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Eisenhower, then Chief of Staff of the Army, to replace President Truman on the Democratic Party ticket.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Eisenhower, who commanded the Allied Expeditionary Force in the invasions of Normandy and Germany, remained broadly popular and admired across the country without regard for political position or region.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] However, Eisenhower repeatedly declined to seek the Democratic nomination ahead of the 1948 convention and issued a Shermanesque statement on July 5, 1948, removing himself from consideration.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Repeated efforts to ignore his statement failed when Roosevelt admitted that a draft would not succeed to convince Eisenhower, and the party nominated Truman instead.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] By 1951, with Truman's popularity polling at record lows, both parties attempted to draft Eisenhower once again.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] However, since the 1948 election, he had been increasingly drawn toward the Republican Party.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Dewey and Senator Henry Cabot Lodge Jr. of Massachusetts led efforts to convince Eisenhower to run as a Republican and, through a series of organizations financed and led by Charles F.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Talbott, established a draft effort with over 250,000 members nationwide.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Personal friends and former military colleagues were also involved in the Republican draft effort.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] With Taft leading the field in late 1951, Eisenhower's reluctance to run declined, and on January 6, 1952, he permitted Lodge to publicly reveal that he considered himself a Republican.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The following persons were listed in two or more major national polls or were the subject of media speculation surrounding their potential candidacy, but declined to actively seek the nomination.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Combined voted for Wayne Morse, James Duff, Alfred Driscoll, Joseph W.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] In late 1951, Eisenhower supporters increased their efforts to draft the general by establishing a campaign organization in New Hampshire, the first state to hold a popular election for delegates.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Governor Sherman Adams endorsed the effort and became the New Hampshire campaign manager for the Draft Eisenhower campaign.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] On January 6, at the same press conference revealing Eisenhower was a Republican, Senator Lodge formally submitted the general's name in the New Hampshire primary.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The draft movement soon gained the endorsement of twenty-four newspapers, led by *The* *New York Times*.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] A Draft Eisenhower rally at Madison Square Garden on February 8 drew a crowd far larger than the arena's capacity; shortly after, Eisenhower privately affirmed that he would contest the presidency, if nominated by the Republicans.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] On March 11, Eisenhower won the New Hampshire primary over Taft by a margin of 12 percent, sweeping all fourteen delegates.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] However, from there until the Republican Convention the primaries were divided fairly evenly between the two men, and by the time the convention opened the race for the nomination was still too close to call.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] When the 1952 Republican National Convention opened in Chicago, most political experts rated Taft and Eisenhower as neck-and-neck in the delegate vote totals.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Eisenhower's managers, led by Governor Dewey and Massachusetts Senator Henry Cabot Lodge Jr., accused Taft of "stealing" delegate votes in Southern states such as Texas and Georgia.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] They claimed that Taft's leaders in these states had illegally refused to give delegate spots to Eisenhower supporters and put Taft delegates in their place.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Lodge and Dewey proposed to evict the pro-Taft delegates in these states and replace them with pro-Eisenhower delegates; they called this proposal "Fair Play".
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Although Taft and his supporters angrily denied this charge, the convention voted to support Fair Play 658–548, and Taft lost many Southern delegates; this decided the nomination in Eisenhower's favor.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] In the end Eisenhower took the nomination on the first ballot; to heal the wounds caused by the battle he went to Taft's hotel suite and met with him.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] The Convention then chose young Senator Richard Nixon of California as Eisenhower's running mate; it was felt that Nixon's credentials as a slashing campaigner and anti-Communist would be valuable.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Most historians now believe that Eisenhower's nomination was primarily due to the feeling that he was a "sure winner" against the Democrats; most of the delegates were conservatives who would probably have supported Taft if they felt he could have won the general election.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Freshman California Senator Richard Nixon was nominated for vice president, also with Dewey's support.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-presidential-primaries] Republican politicians thought that his political experience, aggressive style (he was known as strongly anti-communist), and political base on the West would help political newcomer Eisenhower.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-vice-presidential-candidate-selection] Dewey, who was an Eisenhower supporter and had organized a pro-Eisenhower delegation from New York to attend the national convention.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-vice-presidential-candidate-selection] In a private meeting following the speech, Dewey suggested to Nixon that he would make a suitable vice presidential candidate to run alongside Eisenhower.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-vice-presidential-candidate-selection] Months after the convention, Eisenhower considered asking Nixon to step down as running mate due to controversy surrounding campaign expenses, but Nixon rallied public opinion with his Checkers speech and remained on the ticket.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-vice-presidential-candidate-selection] The Eisenhower–Nixon ticket won the 1952 election, defeating the Stevenson–Sparkman ticket, as well as the 1956 election, in which they defeated the ticket of Stevenson and Kefauver.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-vice-presidential-candidate-selection] Nixon was the Republican presidential nominee in 1960 but lost to John F.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-republican-party-vice-presidential-candidate-selection] He lost the election for California governor in 1962, but was elected president in 1968 and 1972.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] A presidential election was held in the United States on November 4, 1952.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The Republican ticket of General Dwight D.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower and Senator Richard Nixon defeated the Democratic ticket of Illinois Governor Adlai Stevenson II and Senator John Sparkman in a landslide victory, becoming the first Republican president in 20 years.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first election since 1928 without an incumbent president on the ballot.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stevenson emerged victorious on the third presidential ballot of the 1952 Democratic National Convention by defeating Tennessee senator Estes Kefauver, Georgia senator Richard Russell Jr., and other candidates.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The Republican nomination was primarily contested by Eisenhower, a general, widely popular for his leadership in World War II, and the conservative Ohio senator Robert A.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Dewey and other party leaders, Eisenhower narrowly prevailed over Taft at the 1952 Republican National Convention.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] He selected youthful California Senator Richard Nixon as his running mate.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] In the first televised presidential campaign, Eisenhower was charismatic and very well known, in sharp contrast to Stevenson.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Truman's handling of the Korean War and the broader Cold War, alleging Soviet spies infiltrated the U.S. government.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Democrats faulted Eisenhower for failing to condemn Senators Joseph McCarthy, William E.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Jenner, and other reactionary Republicans, who, the Democrats alleged, engaged in reckless and unwarranted attacks.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stevenson tried to separate himself from the unpopular Truman administration.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Instead, he campaigned on the popularity of the New Deal and stoked fears of another Great Depression under a Republican administration.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower retained his enormous popularity from the war, as was seen in his campaign slogan, "I Like Ike".
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower received over 34 million votes, which at the time was the highest popular vote total a presidential candidate had received, surpassing Franklin D.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Republicans gained among Democrats, especially urban and suburban Southerners, and White ethnic groups in the Northeast and Midwest.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The fight for the Republican nomination was between General Dwight D.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower, who became the candidate of the party's moderate Eastern Establishment; Senator Robert A.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Taft from Ohio, the longtime leader of the party's conservative wing; Governor Earl Warren of California, who appealed to Western delegates and independent voters; and former Governor Harold Stassen of Minnesota, who still had a base of support in the Midwest.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The moderate Eastern Republicans were led by New York Governor Thomas E.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Dewey, the party's presidential nominee in 1944 and 1948.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The moderates tended to be interventionists who felt that the country needed to fight the Cold War overseas and confront the Soviet Union in Eurasia.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] They were also willing to accept most aspects of the social welfare state created by the New Deal in the 1930s but sought to reform the programs to be more efficient and business-friendly.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The moderates were also concerned with ending the Republicans' losing streak in presidential elections and felt that the popular Eisenhower had the best chance of beating the Democrats.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] For that reason, Dewey declined the notion of a third run for president despite his large amount of support within the party.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The Republicans had been out of power for 20 years, and there was a strong sentiment that a proper two-party system needed to be re-established.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] It was also felt that the party winning the White House would have more incentive to rein in radicals and demagogues such as Wisconsin Senator Joseph McCarthy.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The conservative Republicans, led by Taft, were based in the Midwest and parts of the South.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The Midwest was a bastion of conservatism and isolationist sentiment.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Dislike of Europeans, in particular the British, was common, and there was a widespread feeling that the British manipulated American foreign policy and were eager to kowtow to the Soviet Union, although such attitudes had begun to change among the younger generation who had fought in World War II.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] In addition, the conservatives opposed much of the New Deal, regarding these programs as diminishing individual liberty and economic freedom.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Taft had unsuccessfully sought the Republican nomination in the 1940 and 1948 presidential elections but lost both times to moderate candidates from New York: Wilkie and Dewey respectively.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] At the age of 63, Taft felt that it was his last chance to run for president so his friends and supporters, encompassing many party regulars, worked diligently on his behalf.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] His feelings were correct, as he died about nine months after the election.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Warren, although highly popular in California, refused to campaign in the presidential primaries, which limited his chances of winning the nomination.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] He retained the support of the California delegation, and his supporters hoped that in the event of an Eisenhower–Taft deadlock, Warren might emerge as a compromise candidate.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] After being persuaded to run, Eisenhower scored a major victory in the New Hampshire primary in which his supporters wrote his name onto the ballot and gave him an upset victory over Taft.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] However, until the Republican National Convention, the primaries were divided fairly evenly between the two, and when the convention opened, the race for the nomination was still too close to call.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Taft won the Nebraska, Wisconsin, Illinois, and South Dakota primaries, and Eisenhower won those in New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Massachusetts and Oregon.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stassen and Warren won only their home states of Minnesota and California respectively, which effectively ended their chances of earning the nomination.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] General Douglas MacArthur also won the support of ten delegates from various states.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] When the 1952 Republican National Convention opened in Chicago, most political experts rated Taft and Eisenhower as about equal in delegate vote totals.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Lodge and Dewey proposed to evict the Taft delegates in those states and replace them with Eisenhower delegates and called the proposal "Fair Play".
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Although Taft and his supporters angrily denied that charge, the convention voted to support Fair Play 658 to 548, and Taft lost many Southern delegates.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower's chances were boosted when several uncommitted state delegations, such as Michigan and Pennsylvania, decided to support him and also when Stassen released his delegates and asked them to support Eisenhower.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The removal of many Southern delegates and the support of the uncommitted states decided the nomination in Eisenhower's favor.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] However, the convention was among the most bitter and emotional in American history.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] In the end, Eisenhower narrowly defeated Taft on the first ballot.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] To heal the wounds caused by the battle, he visited Taft's hotel suite and met with him.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Taft issued a brief statement congratulating Eisenhower on his victory, but he was bitter about the accusation that he had stolen delegates and withheld his active support for Eisenhower for several weeks after the convention.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] In September 1952, Taft and Eisenhower met again at Morningside Heights, in New York City.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower agreed to the terms, and Taft campaigned assiduously for the Republican ticket.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] In fact, Eisenhower and Taft agreed on most domestic issues, and their disagreements were primarily on foreign policy.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Though there were initial suggestions that Warren could earn the party's vice-presidential slot for the second successive election if he withdrew and endorsed Eisenhower, he ultimately chose not to do so.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower wished to award the vice-presidential nod to Stassen, who had endorsed Eisenhower and held generally similar political positions.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] However, the party bosses wanted to find a running mate who could mollify Taft's supporters, as the schism between the moderate and conservative wings was so severe that it was feared that party's conservatives would run Taft as a third-party candidate.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower had apparently given little thought to choosing his running mate.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] When asked, he replied that he assumed the convention would pick someone.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The spot ultimately fell to the young California Senator Richard Nixon, who was viewed as a centrist.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Nixon was known as an aggressive campaigner and a fierce anti-communist but as one who shied away from some of the more extreme ideas of the party's right wing, including isolationism and the dismantling of the New Deal.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Most historians now believe that Eisenhower's nomination was the result of his perceived electability against the Democrats.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Most of the delegates were conservatives who would probably have supported Taft if they felt that he could win the general election.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Despite not earning the presidential or the vice-presidential nomination, Warren would be appointed as Chief Justice of the United States in October 1953, and Stassen would hold various positions within Eisenhower's administration.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The expected candidate for the Democratic nomination was the incumbent President Harry S.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Since the newly passed 22nd Amendment did not apply to whoever was president at the time of its passage, he was eligible to run again.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] However, Truman entered 1952 with his popularity plummeting, according to polls.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Polls showed that he had a 66% disapproval rating, a record that would be matched only decades later by Richard Nixon and surpassed by George W.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Truman's main opponent was the populist Tennessee Senator Estes Kefauver, who had chaired a nationally televised investigation of organized crime in 1951 and was known as a crusader against crime and corruption.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The Gallup poll of February 15 showed Truman's weakness.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Nationally, Truman was the choice of only 36% of Democrats, compared with 21% for Kefauver.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Among independent voters, however, Truman had only 18%, and Kefauver led with 36%.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] In the New Hampshire primary, Kefauver upset Truman by winning 19,800 votes to Truman's 15,927 and capturing all eight delegates.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Kefauver graciously said that he did not consider his victory "a repudiation of Administration policies, but a desire ... for new ideas and personalities".
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stung by that setback, however, Truman announced March 29 that he would not seek re-election.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Truman insisted in his memoirs, however, that he had decided not to run for re-election well before his defeat to Kefauver.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] With Truman's withdrawal, Kefauver became the frontrunner for the nomination, and he won most of the primaries.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Other primary winners were Senator Hubert Humphrey, who won his home state of Minnesota; Senator Richard Russell Jr. from Georgia, who won the Florida primary, and the diplomat W.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Averell Harriman, who won West Virginia.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] However, most states still chose their delegates to the Democratic Convention by state conventions, which meant that the party bosses, especially the mayors and governors of large Northern and Midwestern states and cities, were able to choose the Democratic nominee.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The bosses, including Truman himself, strongly disliked Kefauver since his investigations of organized crime had revealed connections between American Mafia figures and many of the big-city Democratic political organizations.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The party bosses thus viewed Kefauver as a maverick who could not be trusted and so refused to support him for the nomination.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Instead, with Truman taking the initiative, they began to search for other more acceptable candidates.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] However, most of the other candidates had a major weakness.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Russell had much Southern support, but his support of racial segregation and his opposition to civil rights for black people led many liberal Northern and Midwestern delegates, pressed by their many black voters, to reject him.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Truman favored Harriman of New York, but the latter had never held an elective office and was inexperienced in politics.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Truman next turned to Vice President Alben W.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Barkley but at 74, he was rejected as being too old by leaders of labor unions.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Other minor or favorite son candidates included Oklahoma Senator Robert S.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Dever, Minnesota Senator Hubert Humphrey, and Arkansas Senator J.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] One candidate soon emerged who seemingly had few political weaknesses, Governor Adlai Stevenson of Illinois.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The grandson of former Vice President Adlai E.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stevenson, he came from a distinguished family in Illinois and was well known as a gifted orator, intellectual, and political moderate.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] In the spring of 1952, Truman attempted to convince Stevenson to take the presidential nomination, but Stevenson said that he wanted to run for re-election as Governor of Illinois.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] However, Stevenson never completely took himself out of the race, and as the convention approached, many party bosses and normally apolitical citizens hoped that he could be "drafted" to run.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The 1952 Democratic National Convention was held in Chicago in the same Coliseum that the Republicans had gathered in several weeks earlier.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Since the convention was being held in his home state, Governor Stevenson, who still proclaimed that he was not a presidential candidate, was asked to give the welcoming address to the delegates.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] He proceeded to give a witty and stirring address that led his supporters to begin a renewed round of efforts to nominate him despite his protests.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] After meeting with Jacob Arvey, the boss of the Illinois delegation, Stevenson finally agreed to enter his name as a candidate for the nomination.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The party bosses from other large Northern and Midwestern states quickly joined in support.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Kefauver led on the first ballot, but he had far fewer votes than necessary to win.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stevenson gradually gained strength until he was nominated on the third ballot.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] After the delegates nominated Stevenson, the convention then turned to selecting a vice-presidential nominee.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] After narrowing it down to Senators John Sparkman, and A.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Mike Monroney, President Truman and a small group of political insiders chose Sparkman, a conservative segregationist from Alabama, for the nomination.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The convention largely complied and nominated Sparkman as Stevenson's running mate.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] He was chosen because of his Southern identity and conservative record, which party leaders hoped would create a balanced ticket.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Sparkman remained in the Senate until his retirement in 1979.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The Eisenhower campaign was one of the first presidential campaigns to make a major and concerted effort to win the female vote.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Many of his radio and television commercials discussed topics such as education, inflation, ending the Korean War, and other issues that were thought to appeal to women.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The Eisenhower campaign made extensive use of female campaign workers, who made phone calls to likely Eisenhower voters, distributed "Ike" buttons and leaflets, and threw parties to build support for the Republican ticket in their neighborhoods.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] On election day, Eisenhower won a solid majority of the female vote.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower campaigned by attacking "Korea, Communism, and Corruption", issues that the Republicans regarded as the failures of the outgoing Truman administration to solve.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The Eisenhower campaign accused the administration of "neglecting Latin America" and thus "leading them into the arms of wily Communist agents waiting to exploit local misery and capitalize on any opening to communize the Americas".
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Charges that Soviet spies had infiltrated the government plagued the Truman administration and became a "major campaign issue" for Eisenhower.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The Republicans blamed the Democrats for the military's failure to be fully prepared to fight in Korea, accused the Democrats of harboring communist spies within the federal government, and criticized the Truman administration for the many officials who had been accused of various crimes.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stevenson hoped to exploit the rift between the conservative Taft Republicans and the moderate Eisenhower Republicans.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] In a speech in Baltimore, Stevenson said, "The GOP elephant has two heads nowadays, and I can't tell from day to day who's driving the poor beast, Senator Taft or the General.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] I doubt that America will entrust its future, its hopes, to the master of a house divided against itself." Stevenson, Truman, and other Democrats campaigning that fall also criticized Senators Joseph McCarthy, William E.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Jenner, and other right-wing Republicans for what they believed were reckless and unwarranted attacks and congressional investigations into leading government officials and public servants.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] In a Salt Lake City speech Stevenson stated that right-wing Republicans were "quick with accusations, with defamatory hints and whispering campaigns when they see a chance to scare or silence those with whom they disagree.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Rudely, carelessly, they invade the field of thought, of conscience, which belongs to God, and not to Senators. ...
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Truman repeatedly criticized Senator McCarthy's character and temperament and called on Eisenhower to repudiate him.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stevenson ridiculed right-wing Republicans "who hunt Communists in the Bureau of Wildlife and Fisheries while hesitating to aid the gallant men and women who are resisting the real thing in the front lines of Europe and Asia. ...
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] They are finally the men who seemingly believe that we can confound the Kremlin by frightening ourselves to death." In return, McCarthy often jokingly confused the names Adlai and Alger, the first name of the convicted Soviet spy Alger Hiss, by stating "Alger, I mean Adlai" in his speeches.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] McCarthy exploited the fact that Stevenson had defended Hiss as innocent despite all of the evidence otherwise.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] McCarthy, in response to Stevenson's criticisms, also stated during the campaign that he would like to get on the Stevenson campaign trail "with a club and make a good and loyal American" out of Stevenson.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Neither Stevenson nor Sparkman had been a part of the Truman administration, and both largely ignored its record, preferred to hark back to the Roosevelt's New Deal achievements, and warned against a repetition of the Great Depression under President Herbert Hoover if Eisenhower was elected.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower's goal to unite the Republican Party for the fall campaign led him to campaign with and endorse several Republicans with whom he was uncomfortable.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Truman, who had once been friends with Eisenhower, never forgot what he saw as a betrayal.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower retained his enormous personal popularity from his leading role in World War II, and huge crowds turned out to see him around the nation.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] His campaign slogan, "I Like Ike", was one of the most popular in American history.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stevenson attracted the support of the young emerging postwar intellectual class, but Eisenhower was seen as more appealing to Main Street.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stevenson was ridiculed in some quarters as too effeminate to be president, which was sometimes used as a euphemism for a male homosexual.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The staunchly-conservative *New York Daily News* called him "Adelaide" Stevenson even though he had a reputation as a ladies' man, divorced in 1949, and remained single throughout 1952.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] A notable event of the 1952 campaign concerned a scandal that emerged when Richard Nixon, Eisenhower's running mate, was accused by several newspapers of receiving $18,000 in undeclared "gifts" from wealthy donors.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] In reality, contributions were by design only from early supporters and limited to $1,000, with full accountability.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Nixon, who had been accusing the Democrats of hiding corruption, suddenly found himself on the defensive.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower and his aides even considered dropping Nixon from the ticket and picking Senator William Knowland as a replacement running mate.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower, who barely knew Nixon, waffled and refused to comment on the incident.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Nixon saved his political career, however, with a dramatic half-hour speech, the "Checkers speech", on live television.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] In this speech, Nixon denied the charges against him, gave a detailed account of his modest financial assets, and offered a glowing assessment of Eisenhower's candidacy.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The highlight of the speech came when Nixon stated that a supporter had given his daughters a gift, a dog named Checkers, and that he would not return it because his daughters loved it.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The "Checkers speech" led hundreds of thousands of citizens nationwide to wire the Republican National Committee to urge the Republican Party to keep Nixon on the ticket, and Eisenhower stayed with him.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Despite the red-baiting of the Republicans' right wing, the campaign on the whole was conducted with a considerable degree of dignity, and Stevenson was seen as reinvigorating a Democratic Party that had become exhausted after 20 years in power and as refreshing its appeal with younger voters.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] He accused Eisenhower of silently tolerating McCarthy's excesses.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stevenson went before the American Legion, a bastion of hardline conservatism, and boldly declared that there was nothing patriotic or American about what McCarthy was doing.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Even with the dignified nature of the campaign, the dislike between the two candidates was visible.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stevenson criticized Eisenhower's noncondemnation of McCarthy and his use of television spots, and Eisenhower, who had initially respected Stevenson, came in time to view him as simply another career politician, which he strongly disliked.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The 1952 election campaign was the first one to make use of the new medium of television, partly by the efforts of Rosser Reeves, the head of Ted Bates, Inc., a leading advertising firm.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Reeves had initially proposed a series of radio spots to Dewey in the 1948 campaign, but Dewey considered them undignified.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Reeves later maintained that Dewey might have won the election if he had been slightly more open-minded.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Studying Douglas MacArthur's keynote speech at the Republican Convention in July, Reeves believed that the general's words were "powerful" but "unfocused" and "all over the map".
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower's public speeches were even worse since he was unable to make his point to the voting public in a clear intelligible manner.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Reeves felt that Eisenhower needed to condense his message down to a few simple easily-digestible slogans.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower at first also fared poorly on television and had a difficult time appearing relaxed and at ease on camera.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The television lighting was not flattering and made him look old and unattractive.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] In particular, his forehead tended to glisten under the lights.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower became upset when the CBS correspondent Dave Schoenbrun pointed that out and suggested him to try to alter his poses to make his forehead less noticeable and to apply makeup so that it would not shine from the lighting.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eventually, he gave in and agreed to those modifications.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Reeves also wanted Eisenhower to not wear his eyeglasses on camera to look younger, but since he could not read the prompter board without them, Reeves devised a large handwritten signboard.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Reeves's television work, although pioneering, was the subject of considerable criticism on the grounds that he was attempting to sell a presidential candidate to the public in the same manner that one might sell a car or a brand of toothpaste.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] He made a point of the fact that he did not watch or even own a television, and the same went for many members of his inner circle.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Both campaigns made use of television ads.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] A notable ad for Eisenhower was an issue-free feel-good animated cartoon with a soundtrack song by Irving Berlin called "I Like Ike".
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] For the first time, a presidential candidate's personal medical history was released publicly, as were partial versions of his financial histories, because of the issues that had been raised in Nixon's speech.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Near the end of the campaign, Eisenhower, in a major speech, announced that if he won the election he would go to Korea to see if he could end the war.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] His great military prestige, combined with the public's weariness with the conflict, gave Eisenhower the final boost he needed to win.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Throughout the entire campaign, Eisenhower led in all opinion polls and by wide margins in most of them.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] To circumvent the local Republican Party organizations, which were mostly controlled by Taft supporters, the Eisenhower forces created a nationwide network of grassroots clubs, "Citizens for Eisenhower".
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Independents and Democrats were welcome, as the group specialized in canvassing neighborhoods and holding small-group meetings.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Citizens for Eisenhower hoped to revitalize the party by expanding its activist ranks and by supporting moderate and internationalist policies.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] It did not endorse candidates other than Eisenhower, but he paid it little attention after he had won, and it failed to maintain its impressive starting momentum.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Instead, it energized the conservative Republicans, which led finally to the Barry Goldwater campaign of 1964.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Longtime Republican activists viewed the newcomers with suspicion and hostility.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] More significantly, activism in support of Eisenhower did not translate into enthusiasm for the party's cause.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] On election day, Eisenhower won a decisive victory by winning over 55% of the popular vote and carrying 39 of the 48 states.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stevenson did not win a single state north of the Mason–Dixon line or west of Arkansas; he did succeed in winning back the four states which Strom Thurmond had won at the previous election, but lost all but five of the states that Truman had won that year.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower took three Southern states that the Republicans had won only once since Reconstruction: Virginia, Florida, and Texas.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] He also carried Tennessee, a state that only voted for Republicans twice after Reconstruction.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] It was the last time the Republicans won Missouri until 1968 and the last time that a Republican won the election without Kentucky.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stevenson's 700-vote win was the smallest percentage margin in any state since Woodrow Wilson had won New Hampshire by 56 votes in 1916.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 3,099 counties/independent cities making returns, Eisenhower won the most popular votes in 2,104 (67.89%) while Stevenson carried 995 (32.11%).
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower won in 21 of the 39 cities with a population above 250,000.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] He won in six of the eight largest Southern cities.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The election was the first in which a computer, the UNIVAC I (and Monrobot III), was used to predict the results; it came within 3.5% of Eisenhower's popular vote tally and four votes of his electoral vote total.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] 339, enacted July 7, 1958) was a legislative act introduced by Delegate E.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] "Bob" Bartlett and signed by President Dwight D.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Through it, Alaska became the 49th U.S. state on January 3, 1959.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] The law was the culmination of a multi-decade effort by many prominent Alaskans, including Bartlett, Ernest Gruening, Bill Egan, Bob Atwood, and Ted Stevens.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] The law was first introduced by James Wickersham in 1916, shortly after the First Organic Act.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] However, due to a lack of interest from Alaskans, the bill was never introduced.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Efforts increased in 1943, with Bartlett's rendition of the act being introduced first in 1947 and 1950, with the backing of President Harry Truman.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] However, due to opposition from powerful southern U.S.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Congressmen, it took until 1958 to pass the law, with the convincing of Bob Bartlett.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Gruening worked on rallying support from Alaskans, launching the Alaska Constitutional Convention in 1956, which elected Bill Egan and Gruening as Shadow U.S.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Senators, and Ralph Rivers as the Shadow U.S.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Representative, working towards pressuring the U.S.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Atwood similarly rallied support by using his job as a trusted news source to rally Alaskans for statehood.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Stevens also authored parts of the Act (namely Section 10).
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Roger Ernst, Seaton's former Assistant Secretary for Public Land Management, said of Stevens: "He did all the work on statehood; he wrote 90 percent of all the speeches.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] From 1867 to 1884, Alaska was considered to be a military district of the United States under the control of the federal government, known as the Department of Alaska.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] From 1884 to 1912, it was organized as the District of Alaska, and from 1912 to 1959, it was organized into the incorporated Territory of Alaska.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Alaskans had sought statehood since as early as the 1920s, though this vision was not realized until the decade after World War II.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Furthermore, during the 1896–1910 gold rush eras (mainly in the Klondike, Nome, and Fairbanks regions), hundreds of thousands of people traveled to Alaska in search of gold.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Several industries flourished as a result, such as fishing, trapping, mining, and mineral production.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Alaska's resources were depleted to the extent that it came to be considered a "colonial economy".
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] However, Alaska was still considered a district, and local governments often had little control over local affairs.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Several issues arose that made it more difficult for Alaska to push toward self-government.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] One of these was the formation of the "Alaska Syndicate" in 1906 by the two industry barons J.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Their influence spread, and they came to control the Kennecott copper mine, steamship and railroad companies, and salmon packing.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] The influence of the Syndicate in Washington D.C. opposed any further movement towards Alaskan home rule.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] James Wickersham, however, grew increasingly concerned over the exploitation of Alaska for personal and corporate interests and took it upon himself to fight for Alaskan self-rule.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] He used the Ballinger–Pinchot affair in order to help achieve this.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] As a result of the affair, Alaska was in the national headlines, and President William Howard Taft was forced to send a message to Congress on February 2, 1912, insisting that they listen to Wickersham.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] In August 1912 Congress passed the Second Organic Act, which established the Territory of Alaska with a capital at Juneau and an elected legislature.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] The federal government still retained much of the control over laws regarding fishing, gaming, and natural resources and the governor was also still appointed by the President.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] In 1916, Wickersham, who was now a delegate to Congress, proposed the first bill for Alaska's statehood.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] The bill, however, failed, partly due to lack of interest among Alaskans in gaining statehood.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Discrimination against the Alaskan Territory made it difficult for Congress to get much done.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Discussion of revising the Second Organic Act took up much time but came to no avail.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Instead, Congress passed the Jones Act (also known as the Merchant Marine Act of 1920) and the White Act of 1924 both of which made the fishing problem worse for Alaskans rather than better.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Alaskans were angered by these two acts and felt they were discriminatory.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Matters were made worse by regional conflicts which drew attention away from the issue of statehood.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] In the 1930s, Alaska was plagued by the Great Depression.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Roosevelt did two significant things for Alaska.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] First, he allowed for 1,000 selected farmers hurt by the depression to move to Alaska and colonize the Matanuska-Susitna Valley, being given a second chance at agricultural success.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Second (and sometimes considered to be more importantly), Roosevelt appointed Ernest Gruening as governor of Alaska in 1939.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Edward Lewis "Bob" Bartlett, who was one of Alaska's territorial delegates to Congress from 1944 to 1958 when he became a U.S. senator representing Alaska, would become one of Gruening's most important allies in supporting the cause for Alaskan statehood.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Alaska's desire for statehood was much aided by the amount of attention it received during World War II.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] After Japan initiated the Aleutian Islands Campaign in June 1942, the territory became an important strategic military base and a key to the Pacific during the war, with a resulting population increase due to the number of American servicemen sent there.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] It remained critically important in deterring Soviet aggression through the Bering Strait during the Cold War.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] However, many barriers still stood between Alaska and statehood.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Many Alaskans, like the Lomen brothers of Nome and Austin E.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] "Cap" Lathrop, who benefited largely from Alaska's small tax base, did not want themselves or their businesses to be hurt financially by the increase in taxes that would result from statehood.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Other Alaskans feared that statehood would result in a flood of more people coming to Alaska, which they didn't want.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] There was enough of a majority, though, that did want statehood so as to be able to pass a referendum for statehood in Alaska in 1946 by a 3:2 vote.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] With the help of the referendum, Bartlett was able to introduce a bill to Congress.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] The bill, however, was immediately shot down by a coalition of Democrats and Republicans.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Republicans feared that Alaska would be unable to raise enough taxes due to its small population and end up as a welfare state while Southern Democrats feared more pro-civil rights congressmen.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] In retaliation, Gruening established the "Alaska Statehood Committee" in 1949.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] He encouraged journalists, newspaper editors, politicians, and members of national and labor organizations to help use their positions and power to make the issue of Alaskan statehood more known.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] He gathered a group of 100 prominent figures, including Eleanor Roosevelt, actor James Cagney, writers Pearl S.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Buck and John Gunther, historian Arthur M.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Schlesinger Jr., and theologian Reinhold Niebuhr, who all stood for the Alaskan cause.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Another bill was introduced to Congress in 1949 and passed in the House by a 186 to 146 vote in 1950.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] However, the bill was then shot down in the Senate, again for fear of adding more Democrats to the 81st Congress (1949–1951), as the Democrats already had 54 seats to 42 Republican seats.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] On February 27, 1952, the Senate by a one-vote margin (45–44) killed the statehood bill for another year, with Southern Democrats having threatened a filibuster to delay consideration.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] In the 1954 State of the Union address, Eisenhower referred to statehood for Hawaii (then a Republican-leaning territory) but not Alaska (then a Democratic-leaning territory).
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] By March, frustrated by Eisenhower's refusal to support statehood for Alaska, a Senate coalition led by Democrats tied the fates of Alaska and Hawaii statehood together as one package.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] The procedural move was backed by some Southern Democrats, concerned about the addition of new votes in the civil rights for blacks movement, in the hope of defeating both measures.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Six members of the Senate Interior and Insular Affairs Committee, including Senator Butler, went to Alaska in order to hold public hearings and see for themselves what the public sentiment was in Alaska.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] In response to the visit, Alaskans would not let Americans forget the cause.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Citizens sent Christmas cards reading "Make [Alaskans'] future bright/Ask your Senator for statehood/And start the New Year right." Women made bouquets of Alaska's flower, the Forget-Me-Not and sent them to members of Congress.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Movements such as "Operation Statehood" also put increasing pressure on Congress.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] "Lack of public interest" could no longer be used as a feasible excuse to prevent statehood.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Frank Heintzleman proposed that Alaska be divided at the 156th meridian west.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] In interest of the growing fervor and enthusiasm toward the cause, a Constitutional Convention was held at the University of Alaska, Fairbanks, in 1955.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] During this convention, Gruening gave a very powerful speech which compared Alaska's situation to the American struggle for independence.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] The famous speech was entitled "Let Us End American Colonialism" and had a very influential impact.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] The convention was highly praised and very emotional.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] The Constitution for Alaska was written up and Alaskans voted and passed the Alaska Constitution in 1956 with overwhelming approval.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] The Constitution was named "one of the best, if not the best, state constitutions ever written" by the National Municipal League.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Another step forward for the cause was taken by the Alaskan adoption of the "Tennessee Plan" which allowed them to elect their delegates to Congress without having to wait for an official act from Congress.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Alaskans therefore elected to Congress Senators Ernest Gruening and William A.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Egan and Representative to the House Ralph J.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Gruening, Egan, and Rivers attended Congress and were politely received, though they were not officially seated or recognized in any way.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] The Alaskan delegation did not give up, however, and worked hard with Bartlett to pressure the Congress into action.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Eventually, with the help of Bartlett's influence, the Speaker of the House, Sam Rayburn, who until 1957 had been an ardent opponent of the Alaskan statehood cause, changed his mind and when Congress reconvened in January 1958, President Eisenhower fully endorsed the bill for the first time.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Johnson promised his commitment to the bill but others still stood in the way, such as Representative Howard W.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Smith of Virginia, Chairman of the powerful Rules Committee, and Thomas Pelly of Washington State who wanted the Alaskan waters to be open to use by Washingtonians.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Senator Prescott Bush of Connecticut stated that Alaska's population was too small, the territory was non-contiguous, economic conditions were unstable and statehood would increase taxes sharply, which would thus disrupt economic development within the state.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Representative Barratt O'Hara attacked the opposition's fear of the act, stating "During my life-time, 10 states have been admitted to the Union and each time opponents raised the arguments of fear and distrust that we have heard in this debate." Representative W.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Debate lasted for hours within both chambers.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Eventually, though, the resistance was able to be bypassed, and the House passed the statehood bill by a 210–166 vote.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] The Senate, which had had its own version of the bill as well as the House's version, finally managed to pass the House's bill through the fervent urging of Bartlett by a 64–20 vote.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] On January 3, 1959, after much struggle and through the efforts of many, Alaska finally became the 49th state of the United States of America after President Eisenhower signed the official declaration.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] All three propositions were approved by Alaskans in a special election held on August 26, 1958.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] On the first question, "Shall Alaska immediately be admitted into the Union as a state?", the result was 40,452 in favor, and 8,010 against.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] In the late 1950s civil rights bills were being introduced in Congress.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] To overcome the Southern Democrats' suppression of the pro-Republican African-American vote, then-Republican Hawaii's prospects for statehood were tied to Alaska's, which many thought would be more Democratic.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] Hawaii statehood was expected to result in the addition of two pro-civil-rights senators from a state which would be the first to have a majority non-white population.
[src:alaska-statehood-act/alaska-statehood-act] This would endanger the Southern minority segregationist Democratic Senate by providing two more pro-civil rights votes to invoke cloture and halt a Senate filibuster.
